# The memory system: map + health

## The short version

Your machine watches everything you and your agents do, writes the good
parts down as pages in the Brain, and a picky curator texts you the best
bits — then records which emoji you react with. The whole loop runs, and
as of the evening of 2026-07-17 the mess around it is gone: the morning
review found eight problems, and by end of day all eight were fixed,
decided, or retired with receipts.

What changed in one day: the nightly condenser's blind spot is fixed and
deployed, the graph rebuild can no longer leak sensitive titles, the
71 GB pile of failed capture uploads is drained (every recoverable byte
verified into the index, an alarm now watches the folder), four dead
memory systems got a funeral instead of a haunting, and retros — the
"lessons learned" the curator always wanted to read — finally have a
writer. What's genuinely open is one honest question: whether your
emoji grades make the curator *smarter*. The bench says one grade
teaches nothing measurable. Keep reacting; ~20–30 grades with both 👍
and 👎 is the dataset that settles it.

This page covers everything that captures, condenses, stores, curates,
delivers, or grades durable knowledge for you and your agents. Verdicts
are `working` (does its job, receipts prove it), `wobbly` (exists but
degraded or fragile), `retired` (deliberately shut down, data archived),
`parked` (stopped, restartable, nothing deleted). Claims trace to the
four morning survey assets plus the repair and cleanup effort ledgers;
links at the bottom.

## The loop in one breath

Everything you and your agents do on flagg becomes raw session capture.
The observer distills that into observation pages in the Brain. Dreams
condense aging pages into rollups. The neat-memory curator reads the
Brain (observations + retros), judges what's worth your attention, and
DMs you the best of it on its own schedule. You react with an emoji, and
that grade flows back into the judge's history for the next beat. The
wiki renders the whole Brain at brain.joelclaw.com. Capture → condense →
store → curate → deliver → grade: every stage runs, and every stage now
has exactly one implementation — the retirements killed the shadow
copies.

## Capture — working, hardened today

Sessions stream into `~/.joelclaw/runs-dev/` and the observer tick
(every 30 minutes) distills activity windows into schema-v1 observation
pages (652 live + 85 archived at the morning survey). Three fixes
landed in the pipeline today, all deployed and receipted:

- **Dead-fallback writers fixed.** The embedded gateway Pi session had
  been POSTing captures to a dead `localhost:3000` fallback (the
  LaunchAgent never exported `JOELCLAW_CENTRAL_URL`); all three writer
  defaults now point at the real worker, and their logs are append-only
  so concurrent sessions can't erase each other's evidence.
- **Empty runs index their metadata.** Valid-but-empty payloads used to
  vanish (202 accepted, nothing written), which stalled replay
  verification. They now upsert the same `runs_dev` row with
  `turn_count: 0` (joelclaw `6877dab1`).
- **Large runs can't blow the pipeline.** The indexing function used to
  pass whole transcripts through Inngest step outputs, which are
  size-capped — a 4.2 MB replay killed it. Steps now reread from disk
  and return counts and hashes only (`c963c47e`); the same 4.2 MB run
  then indexed clean (570 turns, SHA verified).

**The outbox is drained.** The retry folder that had silently
accumulated 14,853 files / 71.4 GB since 06-08 was analyzed
(read-only), collapsed to 179 logical capture groups (14,591 files were
strict prefixes of later bodies), and replayed through a
dry-run-first, checkpointed, SHA-verified tool: **167 replay requests →
123 indexed + 44 covered by existing captures, 0 failed.** The raw
source files still sit in the outbox pending a deletion check-in — but
an alarm now watches the folder from the observer's self-maintenance
tick (warning at 25 files / 256 MiB / 60 min, critical at 100 files /
1 GiB / 6 h; observer release `01b81cba`), so a silent 71 GB pile-up is
structurally impossible now.

## Condense (dreams) — fixed, deployed, first real night pending

The starvation bug is dead: eligibility is now computed over the whole
corpus and the cap bounds the night's work instead of blinding it
(observer `461eddc8`, 87 tests). Promoted to release the same day via
the new receipt-checked promotion script — in time for the corpus's
first eligibility wave (~07-18, dream fires 06:10). Verdict moves to
`working` when the first unattended dream writes rollups; the machinery
itself is proven (the supervised 07-14 run condensed 85 pages into 26
rollups at 0.81 compression).

Release drift, the disease that let old curator code run in production,
also got its cure: `bin/promote-release.sh` (clean-tree gate, smoke
checks, dry-run receipt, log) plus a release-drift warning in the
self-maintenance tick. Three receipted promotions ran today.

## Retros — writer built and live

The gap is closed. `joelclaw retro <brief-path>` fires
`memory/retro.requested`; the `memory-retro-writer` function reads the
closed brief and its steps' Result sections, enforces the noise bar
(fewer than three steps and no decision ledger → skip with a warning;
the retro must say what changed durable behavior, not re-narrate the
ledger), condenses via pi, and atomically writes one `.svx` into the
retros store the curator already reads (joelclaw `8f127255`, 7 tests).
Agent hooks and steering sessions call the one-liner at effort close.
The curator's best source finally flows.

## Store + render — working

Four registered Brain roots (`user`, `joelclaw`, `observer`, `wiki`)
render at brain.joelclaw.com with privacy exclusions applied. Known
edges, unchanged priority: 27 orphan `.brain` trees on flagg await
per-tree onboarding judgment, and the `.svx` ratchet only runs in
joelclaw-wiki's lint.

## The graph — safe to rebuild

The sharp edge is gone: a shared `isExcludedBrainPage` boundary runs at
build time plus read-path stripping, and `graph:build` is now part of
the normal wiki build (wiki `bc05d5b`). First safe rebuild: 3,082 nodes,
0 sensitive, 0 excluded. The graph refreshes with every build instead of
rotting as a stale manual artifact.

## Curate — working

The neat-memory curator paces itself (judge-named beats, 2h–48h clamp,
dead-man LaunchAgent as revival only), draws from observations + retros,
sends at score ≥ 8, and dedupes forever against sent state. The beat
chain stayed alive through the whole repair day. Its source pool got
strictly better today: retros now flow, and the retired stores can no
longer masquerade as candidates.

## Deliver — wobbly, unchanged by design

DMs ride the legacy notify path, which works. The rebuilt Chat SDK
acting path stays dark behind its flag pending the supervised re-flip
with the visible-delivery canary — owned by the messaging-stabilization
effort, deliberately out of scope for the memory repairs. Wobbly means:
two truths, the fixed one source-verified but not production-verified.

## Grade — plumbing proven; learning honestly unproven

The full pipe is real: your reaction flows poller → bus → flowId bridge
→ grading consumer → atomic outcome write → judge's `{{history}}` next
beat. Your 👍 graded `2026-07-17-248a3715344a` to `worked` end to end.
The learning question got a real bench instead of vibes: 15 paired
sol:xhigh runs over identical candidate pools — real history vs
outcomes-nulled vs flipped-negative — produced **identical picks and
scores**. One grade teaches nothing measurable. The decisive rerun
needs ~20–30 graded sends with both polarities; the
[soul-principles](/joelclaw/projects/soul-principles/soul-principles-brief/)
seed slate will generate exactly that graded volume as a side effect.

## The funerals — four retirements, all receipted

- **Legacy recall stack — retired.** `joelclaw recall` and voice recall
  now answer from the Brain/observation stores (19 tests). The stale
  `memory_observations` index (28,050 docs, 99.26% stale) was archived
  to NAS (238 MB, SHA-verified receipt) and dropped from live
  Typesense. The reflect/promote/proposal/batch-review zombie functions
  and the MEM/FRIC suites protecting them are deleted — one migration,
  −6,306 lines (joelclaw `a673d5c1`).
- **System log — retired with a 21-gun salute.** It froze on 06-22 and
  nobody noticed for 25 days: a ritual, not a system. Panda's copy
  (3,981 lines, the real history) is snapshotted to NAS with a SHA
  receipt; the `slog` write path, system-logger function, and its
  sync/backup/PDS hooks are removed. Runtime evidence is OTel events;
  durable receipts are Brain `.svx` — the jobs it pretended to do,
  done by the things that actually do them.
- **Chorus / rhizomatic — parked.** Session-start briefing injection
  removed from claude/codex/pi configs, the 13-mutation outbox
  snapshotted byte-for-byte before discard, and the service stopped and
  disabled (verified: launchd can't find it, disabled map shows it,
  port 4821 dead). Nothing deleted; the un-park path is documented. If
  claim-graph ideas return, they return as a Brain-owned projection.
- **Claude auto-memory — demoted to pointer index.** All 18 topic pages
  dispositioned: 5 facts that lived nowhere durable migrated to Brain
  `.svx` (fleet-synced), 13 duplicates receipted, 3 stale claims
  flagged rather than blindly migrated, topic pages deleted. MEMORY.md
  is now a binding rule plus one-line pointers into the Brain — useful
  recall real estate, zero shadow content.

The fleet knows: 24 skills plus AGENTS/SYSTEM docs were swept the same
day so no standing surface describes the retired machinery as live
(joelclaw `4476d007`, dark-wizard pushed, grafts refreshed).

## What deserves work next

The morning's eight-item fix list is complete. What's genuinely open:

1. **Outbox source deletion** — the 71 GB of raw files is fully
   dispositioned (indexed/covered/redundant with SHA receipts) but not
   yet deleted; that's a deliberate check-in, not an oversight.
2. **Grade volume** — react to DMs; the taste bench reruns at ~20–30
   grades with both polarities.
3. **First unattended dream** (~07-18 06:10) — confirms the cap fix in
   the wild.
4. **Chat SDK acting re-flip** — messaging-stabilization owns it.
5. **[Soul principles](/joelclaw/projects/soul-principles/soul-principles-brief/)**
   — the chartered next chapter: an earned, capped constitution
   injected into steering surfaces, seeded from this system's receipts
   and graded through the taste gate.

